subSection.paragraph:
Social living has been reported in a wide range of animal taxa, although explanations for why sociality exists are controversial, largely due to its complexity in nature (
Bourke, 2011
). These living arrangements, also termed social structures, can be described as either solitary (an individual arrangement), paired (two individuals living together, either a dyad or reproductive pair) or group forming (
Rubenstein & Abbot, 2017
). While these structures suggest a form of permanency (e.g., monogamous pairings or eusocial groups for joint defence and offspring care) (Duffy, 2002; 

Duffy 
et al
., 2002

; 
Duffy & Macdonald, 2010
; 

Chak 
et al
., 2015

; 

Hultgren 
et al
., 2017

), they can also be formed temporarily (e.g., temporary mate guarding) (
Mathews, 2003
; 
Baeza & Díaz-Valdés, 2011
). These arrangements can be described as strict (wherein species typically never deviate from their chosen lifestyle) (Duffy, 2002; 

Duffy 
et al
., 2002

; 
Duffy & Macdonald, 2010
) or facultative (in which a given species can be seen to have several 
types
of social arrangements) (
Lott, 1984
, 
1991
; 

Wong 
et al
., 2005

; 

Hernáez 
et al
., 2021

). Understanding the nature of social associations is important as they can influence individual fitness, but also because they are often linked to or influence the surrounding ecosystem as many species play vital roles in maintaining their habitats, i.e., ecosystem engineers (
Berkenbusch & Rowden, 2003
; 
Pillay, 2019
). With this in mind, environmental change can severely impact these interactions, leading to extensive consequences for the wider community. For example, impacts on ecosystem engineers could have effects on the surrounding ecosystem as their role has both direct and indirect effects on community composition (

Jones 
et al
., 1994

; 
Coleman & Williams, 2002
; 
Moore, 2006
). Gaining an understanding of animal social structures is therefore vital to ensure all species maintain their roles, and to ensure the continued functioning of the ecosystems they reside in.

Marine invertebrates have the potential to exhibit an array of different social structures and can generate novel insights into current theories of social evolution ( Duffy & Thiel, 2007 ;
Hultgren et al ., 2017
; Rubenstein & Abbot, 2017 ;
Hernáez et al ., 2021
). For example, the snapping shrimp Synapheus
regalis ( Duffy, 1996 )
lives within the canals of sponges (
Hultgren et al ., 2017
) and display eusociality, whereby individuals reside in large groups. This results in overlapping generations and a division of labour for defence and offspring care (Duffy, 2002;
Duffy et al ., 2002
; Duffy & Macdonald, 2010 ;
Chak et al ., 2015
;
Hultgren et al ., 2017
). The group’s reproductive individuals typically consist of one queen and her mate (Duffy, 2002;
Duffy et al ., 2002
), while the remaining non-breeding group members are allocated to parental care or colony defences (Duffy, 2002;
Duffy et al ., 2002
;
Hultgren et al ., 2017
). Kinship is thought to be the main factor promoting sociality in species of snapping shrimps, owing to high genetic relatedness between breeders and non-breeders (
Hultgren et al ., 2017
; Rubenstein & Abbot, 2017 ; Subramoniam, 2017 ). In comparison, many other species of decapods live in pairs with monogamous mating systems (i.e., Alpheidae , Hippolytidae , Palaemonidae , and Pinnotheridae ) ( Correa & Thiel, 2003 ; McDermott, 2005 ;
Baeza et al ., 2016
;
Alves et al ., 2021
); for example, the burrowing shrimp
Alpheus bellulus ( Miya & Miyake, 1969 )
only occurs in monogamous pairs as adults with the pair-bond forming early in their life ( Yanagisawa, 1984 ; Boltaña & Thiel, 2001 ; Mathews, 2002 , 2003 ). It is believed that
A. bellulus
pair bonds form due to the benefits of joint burrow defence and maintenance, and the provision of a readily accessible mate. Finally, certain species of shrimps are solitary, like the ascidian-associated shrimps
Ascidonia flavomaculata ( Heller, 1864 )
and
Ascidonia miserabilis ( Holthuis, 1951 )
, which live solitarily within a branch of the host ascidian due to competition for resources (i.e., shelter and food) ( Baeza & Díaz-Valdés, 2011 ;
Pachelle et al ., 2012
). Only temporary mating pairs form, whereby males leave the safety of their shelter in search of females, and males subsequently leave once brooded embryos are established, suggesting a temporary mate guarding system within an overall solitary social structure ( Baeza & Díaz-Valdés, 2011 ;
Pachelle et al ., 2012
).

While various studies have investigated the social structure of sponge-dwelling shrimps and other crustaceans, burrowing mud shrimps, otherwise known as callianassid shrimp (
Callianassidae Dana, 1852
) have been somewhat overlooked. Callianassid shrimps typically have elongated, fragile soft bodies that are protected by calcified plates along the dorsal length of their bodies, as well as possessing three sets of pleopods for swimming and two chelipeds (one of which is enlarged) ( Hailstone & Stephenson, 1961 ). Their highly cryptic lifestyles make detailed quantification of their social structures much more challenging, as their subterranean burrows allow them to hide and otherwise avoid exposure. As a result, relatively little is known about their social and mating associations ( Hernáez & João, 2018 ;
Hernáez et al ., 2021
, 2022 ) compared to their reproductive and population biology (
Stamhuis et al ., 1996
;
Coelho et al ., 2000
;
Dworschak et al ., 2006
). Social and mating systems have typically been inferred indirectly, establishing a lack of empirical studies that directly quantify mating and social associations ( Hailstone & Stephenson, 1961 ; Felder & Lovett, 1989 ; Rowden & Jones, 1994 ;
Coelho et al ., 2000
;
Mariappan et al ., 2000
;
Candisani et al ., 2001
;
Bilodeau et al ., 2005
;
Shimoda et al ., 2005
; Butler & Bird, 2008 ;
Kinoshita et al ., 2010
;
Hernáez et al ., 2021
). An understanding of the causes and consequences of sociality in these callianassid shrimps is essential as they are important ecosystem engineers that affect the surrounding environment and the biota residing in it (
Jones et al ., 1994
; Berkenbusch & Rowden, 2003 ). Behaviour can influence ecological outcomes (i.e., predator-prey, community assembly, human disturbance, ecosystem engineers), and therefore any change in the behaviour or structure of a species can change the ecosystem as a whole. As a result, we must gain a better understanding of their social and reproductive associations to ensure these roles are continued to maintain a functioning ecosystem.

Sampling at each of the three sites was conducted two to three hours before low tide in the mid-low intertidal zone. To collect the shrimp, a typical burrow opening was randomly selected and pumped four to six times with a standard nipper pump ( 76 cm in length, 5 cm diameter).As these burrows can have multiple openings (a typical burrow as described by Butler & Bird (2008)) , a minimum of one-meter distance between burrows and areas where burrows were less densely orientated were selected to avoid the potential of resampling the same burrow. This methodology has been used effectively in several studies ( Contessa & Bird, 2004 ; Hailstone & Stephenson, 1961 ;
Rotherham , 2004
; Hernáez & João, 2018 ;
Hernáez et al ., 2021
, 2022 ). Each shrimp from a burrow was collected and assigned individual burrow and shrimp identification numbers. Shrimp were secured on a board, and scaled photographs of the ventral side of each individual were taken for later verification of sex and size ( Fig 1 ). Sex was determined by the presence of the second pair of pleopods, which are absent in males and present in females (
Rotherham , 2004
). The carapace length and the propodus of the enlarged cheliped length were measured to the nearest 0.1mm using plastic callipers and recorded on waterproof paper. The position (left or right) of the major cheliped was also recorded. After measurements were taken, shrimp were then released back to an adjacent area where they were pumped from and monitored until they had safely burrowed again.

